segments.text: how to make politics more, how to end corruption in politics.
I'm an optimist.
I wouldn't have been running that many times.
I wouldn't have spent everything earned on political campaigns.
I'd be working dead now in the law practice, the solo practice stage of 81.
But I spent, I made good money practicing law, spent it and raised it because I couldn't raise much money, very little money.
run because of my positions and what I've done.
They knew the first time I ran for statewide office for Attorney General, 38.
From those suits I tried to eat, what I knew, they bought me from the beginning.
I'd already served notice.
I'd fanned the best they could put up in the courtroom.
And it wasn't that easy out on the stump, where money counts more.
And it's a big state with many millions of people.
widened and dispersed over the state, and it's expensive getting a message out to them.
I took campaign after campaign before I could get well enough acquainted to win.
The Texas Observer pointed out in 1972 that, quote, Yarborough proved in three terms in the U.S. Senate that a strong person can hold high office and remain uncorrupted, unquote.
Do you think this is still possible today?
And if so, how do you think, who do you think are examples of this, both in Washington and Austin?
Well, I think that, surely I think it's possible today.
And I don't think that I kicked myself letting them take that office away from the people when I was defeated.
But I had my Cold War GI Bill amendments to make it stronger finally passed in March or in April with the primary in May.
I think if I had come back down here three or four months before that campaign, I don't think I would have lost even without money.
But the fact that I was there passing those bills, I was passing major bills.
I passed the OSHA, the Occupational Health and Safety Bill.
chairman of that full committee and I made them come in and threatened to open the doors and invite the press and read to the Lord who was breaking the form if they didn't.

That's kind of unprotocol-ish but it was my last year I was defeated and I was determined to get it passed and did in December of 1970 and I passed the biggest, we needed the hospitalization badge at the end, I passed the biggest hospital bill in the history of the country because
for the first time, instead of just building a new hospital, to put money in there to renovate an old one, to build an additional wing.
There's a lot of wastage in it.
You couldn't touch an old hospital, but just build a new one.
We put those amendments on there that amounted to, the paper said, $5,700,000,000.
It was about a year.
That's about five years.
Well, Nixon vetoed it.
I'd been defeated.
And when you're sponsoring a deal, you're the author and the sponsor and chairman of the health subcommittee.
the majority leader of the Democrats when the majority doesn't handle a bill in the Senate by hand making you stand up and present it and try to pass it.
You do it yourself, y'all.
So passed it all right.
Nixon vetoed it.
He felt safe about it because no lame duck senator had passed a bill over a presidential veto in 57 years.
I passed that hospital bill over Nixon's veto first
The first one since the direct election of the United States Senators had started in 1913.
The first time that a lamed up Senator had passed a bill for the President's veto.
And that was one of my kudos that I had.
But, so, yes, if I had to come back here and just, and people warned me.
Russell Long told me, he said, he just quit and left about five months before his election.
He said, I figured my election was more important than these bills that came up a few months here.
And I had my bills, and I worked on them there, and didn't get back here.
They made great hay of that, very effective hay.
They said, look there, he's got the tonic fever, got the .
Has he been back in your county this past year, two years, three years?
Well, when I went there, the Congress was in session about eight or nine months a year.
But those latter years,
They were in session 12 months a year.
Of course, now they take a recess in the summer and take another fall.
They weren't taking other weekends.
They're working 12 months through, and that was beating us Democrats because we weren't.
That's what helped break the common cause, plus the fact that it wouldn't take any vacation time or help eliminate those Democratic majorities in Congress.
Who do you think are examples of strong, uncorrupted leaders, both in Washington and Austin?
Well, there are plenty.
I'm not there on the ground enough to know and to see them and to know.
I can only speak from what you read in the newspapers.
When I was there with all the information you gathered from different sources, newspaper men, staff and all, you knew.
But I don't know now.
I know over in the Senate, the people that I consider incorruptible, Cranston, California,
ran a very poor race for the presidency because he was bald and wasn't handsome.
And then he got sick in the middle of it.
He's the oldest one running, and it's terrible for the oldest one to get sick.
And it liquidated him.
And Edward Kennedy of Massachusetts there, absolutely financially improper, but you can't touch them.
They're richer than anybody else.
If somebody come in and try to insult one of them to bribe him, I don't think it's ever happened.
He did.
He'd be, of course, that's not true of all men.
Some are so greedy they want more and more all the time.
Not the Kennedys.
They're dedicated people.
I served on the committee with all three of the Kennedy brothers.
They all got on that committee because that's where you could pass legislation to help people.
And I figured up last year the total number of years I was serving with the Kennedy brother on that committee was over 15.
Because sometimes two of them would be on there at one time, Ted Kennedy and Robert Kennedy.
and I do serve them, but they are.
There are plenty of others.
I just don't know them as well as, I think, the one in that category was Joe Clark of Pennsylvania.
I mentioned him earlier.
There are a lot of them.
How about here in Austin?
Most of them, though, let me say this.
Most of them who are incorruptible don't walk around saying, I'm not a crook, I'm an honest man.
They think that virtue is its own role.
They don't go around.
The man goes around saying, I don't take money on the table.
I'm an honest man.
You'd better look out for it.
You'd better start peeping on the table, see when it's reaching for it.
How about in Austin?
Well, not that close.
In fact, no, we are not that close up there, out of that hundred.
And A1 people, there are plenty of incorruptible people.
Plenty.
Some on the other side, too.
What do you think the administration of President Reagan's, the effects of the administration have been on the United States, particularly in the areas of education and child welfare?
It's been a disaster, an unlimited disaster.
The great American historian, I think the greatest living historian, Mr. Steele Cumminger, you know, he says that this administration
is the least compassionate administration in all the history of America.
The whole history is down on that weight.
They have cut hundreds of thousands out of colleges.
They'll never have an opportunity to go.
We built that up.
I told you about $11 million I left there, and the bills we passed, they built it up at one time to $13 million.
There are 139 colleges in Texas, 66 lost enrollment last fall and lower enrollments than there were before.
I'll give a sample of One Direction.

We had passed a bill there to provide that in the case the parents died before they were old enough to get, go there and work and grow their social security, and many do through terrible crashes on the old, on the highways and so bad, and through occupation and safety.
Our occupation and safety laws are the weakest of any industrial measure in the world.
and many are killed in the industry, leaves the young children without the breadwinner there.

So we passed the law that they could go to college four years, not beyond their 22nd year, not to lure them back in if they'd raised a family of 45 or something while they were young, a chance to have a maximum four years college education.
By January of 1981, when Reagan took office, there were 700,000 of those in college
And the spring, not of this year, but of last year, that was $250,000 less.
He got an executive order.
He entered an executive order, and he had the power to do that.
Not to take anybody out of college, but to cut off, to modify.
And this reform they were talking about of Social Security cut out that $700,000 in college.
The last of them were there, and $55,000 would be there last year.
It had been cut down then to have $250,000 less, and
about $360,000 less in college and cutting it constantly.
I don't know what it is this year.
It's much less than that.
And $455,000 would be that last year.
Now, I've talked to the admissions officer out here to give you a sample of how this works.
The admissions officer last year, I don't have the September figures, but up through the spring of 84, three years of Reaganomics.
There were 19,500 students at the University of Texas out of the some 45,000 there who were going to the university under some form of federal grant loan or grant or a combination of them.
That had fallen by last spring of 84 to 14,500, 5,000 less.
That's over 25% in three years in all categories together, just over 25% less.
dropped, fallen in enrollment, but they've got more fluent students in there.
There's room for others, there's more money to come in.
And then another category, they, we had the National Defense Education Loans.
That was to lend money to students whose, whose wealth was such they couldn't come in on the poverty programs, but their parents could borrow money
They could borrow money, but the federal government insured it.
They insured the loans.
Many men's college owned insured U.S. loans, borrowed from banks, savings and loans, credit unions, anywhere like that.
Credit placed the federal government insuring the loan.
Now, they changed the criteria.
They required, under Reagan, that for that student to borrow, the family had to go on the note, the parents or the guardian, and they had to be able to pay it back if the student couldn't.
That made the family the insurer rather than the U.S. government.
The U.S. government insured it, but the family was standing in between.
And that took out the students that had no family resources to borrow that money to pay it back if they couldn't.
And that pushed that group into upper echelon bracket, the family with the wealth to pay it back if the student couldn't.
Now, with those two categories, the admission officer out here told me, he said,
The tragedy of this is seeing both categories lose.
It's what you'd call the lower middle income group that we lose in students among whom we find some of the greatest dedication, some of the hardest work, some of the greatest desire to succeed.
But from that group, asking who the lower middle class is, they're not going to tell you that.
You find out yourself.
But you go look at the income tax returns in the World Almanac, you can find those categories of what they earn and so forth.
And in certain categories, there are many categories, but they give some big ones.
School teachers, policemen, firemen, small farmers, small businessmen, people in the middle class, called middle class, but in lower income groups.
Their children are out.
And they said they had those parents were killed.
No other way to go to college.
No other way where they lost their credit.
That's the economics of the Reagan era.
It's a disaster.
And if it keeps on, they're going to be fewer.
And it's heightened here in Texas where they're fixing to triple or quadruple or quintuple the tuition per hour that students pay in state-supported institutions of higher learning.
That's going to worsen it here in Texas when Reagan has gotten the Congress to go along with him to cut down on this at the national level, cutting deeply into student aid.
And then the state raises the tuition.
They've been paying it out at the same time.
It's going to be a disaster.
And what Texas is doing, the other states are probably going to do there.
Raising tuition to make up for the federal money and all that.
And if this keeps on another four years, unless the Congress takes hold and kicks Reagan in the shins and back in, then they ought to run the education on all sides.
They ought to just beat them on all sides if they have any nerve.
It's kind of a bunch of gutless wonders that all this happened, except they didn't say nothing.
They said, so mildly, they wonder whether they mean this or not.
They ought to be shouting from the housetops.
People will look back at the 60s and 70s in the future, if this continues, as the golden age of American education.
Most students had a chance.
Most of all the young people had a chance to get an education.
When you were a senator from Texas...
The Texas press didn't cover you very often.
There was sort of a press blackout.
Yeah.
What do you attribute that to?
Oh, the fact that the big money in Texas was opposed to me.
I was voting for people.
They weren't students.
You didn't.
I was partially responsible.
I didn't put a lot of press releases out about all these bills that are passing for education.
Of course, they had the people of Texas brainwashed against that.
So that federal money, the $8,

I was out in the panhandle that they were dedicating a dam where I'd got money, and had a school that had grown up on the banks of that lake up there on the Canadian River, and I said, did you get that aid?
The trooper in there says, no, we don't want any of that federal money in here.
We're Texans.
We're Texans.
He wouldn't accept federal aid.
He had his kids more poorly educated than those in some other districts.
Because he didn't get that money for the scientific equipment.
He didn't have it for the language, all these boos.
where each kid in his foreign language class in high school had his own booth satisfied with the money he put in on the National Defense Education Program.
What do you see as the future of the Democratic Party?
Back to your other question.
Another reason for that, I complained to the Associated Press when I had releases.
I had some bills I prayed about, especially my park bills and all, about the unfair treatment I was getting compared to the...
to the, uh, the tower, the Republican Center, and all.

In fact, they had no notice of what I was doing, just, they were trying to make people believe I was a married man, and then completely no influence of what they were really trying to do, so they could beat me in the next election.
Well, uh, he, uh,
AP says, we've checked that.
We send this out.
There's a regional distribution point.
Kansas City, I believe, said, we're giving you a fair break.
All the stories going out of Washington, we're giving you a fair break.
He says, the paper's infected.
Don't worry.
It's not cut out here in Washington.
It's cut out down at the lower level.
And they say, well, what they don't want.
And they just wouldn't take anything.
I got some good publicity out of it.
Negatively, if they had something attacking me,
Sometimes that didn't get in because I had orders to cut every story with my name in them.
Sometimes they'll attack me.
I'd say it wouldn't be in the Texas paper.
The general orders, cut your articles.
Some didn't take the trouble to read it and discriminate.
Just don't give them any publicity.
I talked to the Wall Street reporter man in Washington one time after I'd been there some years, about 10 years, I said, see, your paper amazes me.
You're supposed to be in the paper with big money and wealth and everything in the country.
I get a fair shake out of Wall Street Journal than I do any big daily newspaper in Texas.
How do you explain that?
He said, we're non-political.
The people that we give the people the news, what happens.
And we figure they're intelligent enough to make their judgment on that, who they want to support and not support.
We tell them what he's doing.
We try to write him a portion of what's actually happening.
Ours is a financial paper.
It's not trying to pump one party, one person against the other.
It's lay it all out there and let the people judge.
And the financials of the people that are able to buy, do buy the Wall Street Journal, we think have been close enough to face certain judgment.
We believe in keeping them informed.
And the result was I had some very friendly articles from Boyle Street Journal for my big ticket bill.
No big newspaper in Texas would write an article in favor of that big ticket bill, not a one.
Now when I had the Padre Island-Niceman seashore bill, I had three papers help me, the Texas Observer here,
The Corpus Christi Caller Times and the Houston Press.
It was a Scripps-Howard paper in Houston that later went under and was absorbed by one of the other two.
There used to be three dailies there.
As the three papers, one was this observer that comes out a couple times a month, and two dailies supported the Padre Island.
The Guadalupe Mountain was better supported.
That was far out in West Texas, and the West Texans wanted some of that.
At the Corpus Christi, Colder Times, Fort Worth, Star-Telegram, and others were pumping for it.
It wasn't as hard to get as the Pottery Isle bill.
But the Big Thicket, Time Life, the most profitable operation of Time Life is not for the mini-magazines in St. Francis or the recreational places they have around the world.
Their biggest income is from those fine plantations down in the Big Thicket, and they were cutting the weight.
First, the Dallas News wrote an article at the beginning before that for the big ticket.
Maybe one other paper.
They soon quit.
We can see what was happening.
They would tell them, here, you are going to run the price of folk paper up here if you let us continue the operation of that Acor's operation.
And already out of 3 and 1 half million, there wasn't but about 300,000 acres left.
We got a measly 85,000, 84,550 acres in the park.
That's all to say they're butchering it now.
The Secretary of Interior and all just giving permits to any driller that wants to go in there and drill those.
The oil was reserved.
The oil was reserved to the landowners.
But we proved at the hearings it's perfectly feasible if there's oil under that to drill it by slant hole drilling.
And I was down there at a big thicket association meeting here
this past winter, and had a meeting there honoring Arthur Fullenkamp, who's dead now, who was a great protagonist of the Big Thicket.
His paper, the Coombs name, said it was red oil over Texas.
He had to sign the big double barrel shotgun, the editor filed fourth barrel.
And he did.
He scorched them.
He scorched them.
We'd reproduce it and mail it over to Texas.
And they fight for the Big Thicket.
And so that fight there, there's nobody left to attack that.
What they're doing, what the former Secretary of the Interior said, that a lot of these areas should be reseeded to the states.
They're not worthy of being a national park area.
So if they butcher that enough, what they plan to do is give it back, reseed Texas and its legislature up here,
there'd be probably some broken legs trying to outrun each other to give it back to the lumber companies.
It'd be a great danger hurting somebody if they rushed to vote for it to give it back.
What do you see as the future of the Democratic Party, primarily here in Texas, but also throughout the United States?
I see the Democratic Party to be very much stronger in 1986 than it was in 1984.
Now, Reagan did not get all this
vote that he got on personal popularity.
I think the press has wholly misprinted that and maybe didn't know.
I don't mean they deliberately lied about it.
They just looked the surface thing at Humphrey.
Democrats are unpopular.
The Democratic Party and what it stood for was not that unpopular.
And Humphrey wasn't.
I mean, Mondale wasn't until he got up and made that acceptance speech and said, I'm going to raise your taxes.
I went out campaigning for
One day, it was the law's cause.
Old friends have known the staunch Democrats all their life.
He said he was going to raise our taxes.
That was the thing that killed him off cold.
Killed the Democratic horse.
It didn't kill the horse, it killed the potential of winning.
I think without that, that kind of blunders, by trying to fire Manette and put Burt Lance in, they may be an honest man, but the whole country regards Burt Lance as a crook.

whether he is or not it was there and then later was oh and the big ones try to pull out to try to pull out of his uh boo-boo on the taxes later says i'm not going to raise any taxes for anybody that makes less than 25 000 a year it'll only be those above that well average airline pilot in the united states average salaries are 75 000 a year steel workers
CWA, communication workers, many of them.
I expect the average is over 25.
Oil, chemical, and atomic workers, I don't know what the average is, 35,000, 40,000.
He lost 40% of labor.
That ran off his more affluent labor workers who could have contributed to his campaign.
He lost their support and all.
So that's the reason that Reagan got that big vote.
It's one reason.
Those politicians in Washington are smart enough and worked it.
They haven't so much trouble with

In Congress now, though, he's got enough bull weevils from Republicans in the House to pass his legislation, and they know it's an abomination, what he's trying to do to the poor people, the child support for the...

He's cutting all the... What he reminds me of more than anything was Hitler prior to World War II when he was cutting all domestic programs in Europe and building up the most powerful offensive war machine in the history of the human race up to that time.

Reagan's following the same pattern, build up a powerful, it's got the most powerful war machine in the world, make it stronger, have the most powerful war machine in the world, cut all these domestic forces and push that back, which is pushing civilization back.
There were...
Wait just a minute.
There were...
1978, there were 24 million people in the poverty bracket in America.
Five years later, under Reaganomics, 35 million.
And if you had an old one, back here when there were, the number below the poverty level was 39 million when Kennedy won.
By the time the Republicans came in, they had it reduced to 25 million.
And that 25 million had the percent below the poverty level
The anti-poverty bills did not fail.
They succeeded wonderfully.
We've had nothing but a barrage of propaganda since Nixon went in to the present that all this was a failure, well-intentioned failure.
It succeeded wonderfully.
Here, between 60 and 70, the percentage of people below the poverty level reduced from 22% to 12%.
It went down to 12%.
Now, 1983, it's back up to 15% and climbing.
and climbing rapidly.
And the number of people in that poverty bracket now are higher than they've been since 1960 when the Democrats won the election.
35 million.
That's just one in this year.
You can take other facts after facts.
Poverty by family status.
Very poor.
All the statistics show the disaster.
The disaster to the people.
Economics.
Here is the total...
I want to take taxes.
Individual.
Come here.
Yeah, just let it go in here.
Okay.
All right.
Individual, look here in fiscal eight before Reagan went in.
Get one of these books and look at it.
You get all kinds.
$244 million was the taxes paid by individuals.
Corporate income tax was $64 million.
Now, three years later,
The total taxes paid to individuals, $288 million, just about 20% over that 24, not quite 20% increase.

But corporation taxes have been cut from $64 to $37 million with the greatest power grabbed by big corporations grabbing over smaller than snow in American history, the biggest profits in American history.
Look at those gross profits of General Motors and their taxes are cut down that way.
The big rich never had such largesse before.

An economist out here at the university has told me that never in the history of mankind has there been such a tremendous shift of wealth from one group to another in a nation except in time of war or revolution.
But in peaceful means, just peaceful laws, taking it away from the middle class and investing it in the very rich.
And if you look at the number of the income tax returns here,
Is this what Reagan calls the Second American Revolution?
Well, it is one.
Yes, it's the Second American Revolution.
Taking property from the poor and giving it to the rich.
It's never happened before in our history to this extent.
The number of returns here of people, if you add all these up, with under $25,000 a year, that's 70% of all income tax returns in the United States.
If you take the number under $50,000 a year,
and add these that get over $50,000, that's 7%.
93% of all the income tax returns are under $50,000.
And that's where you look at the millions of the number of returns and the gross income, where the income's coming in, in those hundreds of billions.
Now, when they cut the income taxes 25%, if you earn under 25%,
you've lost money because they've raised the local taxes.
Look everywhere.
Your school taxes and all make up for this.
If you're earning under $50,000, you've probably lost.
Probably lost.
You may not.
Your family situation may be such that you didn't lose.
But generally.
You've lost if you're under $50,000.
That's 93% of all the returns.
It's just robbing you of the others.
And people are swallowing that because the press is big money and it's helped put this fake thing over.
It's on myths, false myths, falsehoods.
And the Democrats are so pitifully weak up there, they're not educating the people.
They'll say it and smile.
My God, you tell somebody he's a criminal, what district attorney could get up and convict a criminal by smiling to the jury?
You know, when you're convicted of robbers and thieves, and you ask about this, well, old Harry Truman was the one who told the truth about that.
Harry Truman said that in his book, Frankly Speaking, if you look at that paperback, it's not this exact word, but that's what it meant.
That the only people who make money out of politics are thieves and crooks.
And you can steal it or take it and drive it.
Thieves and crooks.
